   <titles>
      <title>Cross Products in Arbitrary Dimensions?</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The operations ‘dot product’ and ‘determinant’ are defined for all dimensions <math>
                     <latex>n\geq 1</latex>
                  </math>. Analogously we would expect a definition of the cross product in dimensions <math>
                     <latex>n\geq 1</latex>
                  </math>. There are two interpretations</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>We look for an alternating and multilinear operation which assigns to an ordered <math>
                           <latex>(n-1)</latex>
                        </math>-tuple of vectors <math>
                           <latex>(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_{n-1})</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> a vector <math>
                           <latex>\text{Cross}(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_{n-1})</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> such that</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\det[\Vect{b}_1\ \ \cdots\ \ \Vect{b}_{n-1}\ \ \text{Cross}(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_{n-1})]</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text> &gt; </text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>0</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_{n-1})</latex>
                        </math> is linearly independent. Such an operation exists, but is usually not referred to as a ‘cross product’.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>We look for an alternating bilinear operation on ordered pairs of vectors <math>
                           <latex>(\Vect{u},\Vect{v})</latex>
                        </math> such that <math>
                           <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{v} }\neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math> whenever <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                        </math> are not parallel, and such that <math>
                           <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{v} }</latex>
                        </math> is perpendicular to both <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>For deeper reasons, such an operation is only possible if <math>
                           <latex>n=3</latex>
                        </math> or <math>
                           <latex>n=7</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Advanced information</strong>   We mention two results on the (non-)existence of cross products of pairs. First a now classical result from algebraic topology:</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Theorem</strong>   Suppose <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> admits a cross product operation satisfying</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math> are not parallel, then <math>
                           <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }\neq 0</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>For all <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x},\Vect{y}\in \RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ (\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }) }{ \Vect{x} }\neq 0</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ (\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }) }{ \Vect{y} }\neq 0</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\CrssPr{-}{-}\from \RNr[n]\times \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> is a continuous function</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
            <para>
               <para.body>Then <math>
                     <latex>n=3</latex>
                  </math> or <math>
                     <latex>n=7</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>If we add to the list of assumptions above the requirement that the cross product be bilinear, then the conclusion of the theorem can be proven by elementary algebraic means. This is a classical theorem of Frobenius.
				</para.body>
               <index.author>
                  <name>
                     <name>
                        <first/>
                        <last>Frobenius</last>
                     </name>
                  </name>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>In connection with the non-existence of cross product operations in dimensions other than <math>
                              <latex>3</latex>
                           </math> and <math>
                              <latex>7</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.author>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
